Imagine you’re Google in the early days of search

The price you charge for ad space is determined by a competitive market, so you can’t charge any price you want. You’re a price-taker.

Over time, you become more like a monopoly

You choose the price you want, and sell as many as the market will demand at that price. You’re a price setter.

The primary difference between a price-taking firm and a monopolist firm

  • Price-taking firm faces a demand curve that is market price.
  • Monopolist firm faces a demand curve that is the actual demand curve.

Source: Krugman and Wells

The primary difference between a price-taking firm and a monopolist firm

The implication is…

If a firm has a monopoly, it can set the price at some point along the demand curve to maximize revenue.

Monopolist maximizes profit across price and quantity

Since choosing the price affects the quantity the monopolist can sell, there are two effects.

For example, if the monopolist increases prices:

  • demand is lower so the firm sells less and revenue is reduced. This is the Quantity Effect.
  • each unit sold is sold at a higher price, so revenue is increased. This is the Price Effect.

Monopolist optimal output

The monopolist chooses quantity at which:

Marginal Cost is equal to Marginal Revenue (MC = MR), but not equal to price.

In a competitive market, MC = MR = Price, but in a monopoly, the price is higher.

Monopolist profit

Source: Krugman and Wells
